Confirmed directly. Here's the answer:

## 1. File/symbol responsible

- **`webclient/src/utils/dates.ts`** — function **`formatRelative(iso: string, now: Date = new Date()): string`** (lines 7–14)

This is the single source of truth. It's called from exactly one place:

- **`webclient/src/components/UserBadge.tsx`** — `{formatRelative(joinedAt)}` in the "joined X ago" text.

No date library (date-fns/dayjs/moment) is used — it's hand-rolled `Date` math, and `webclient/package.json` has zero dependencies.

## 2. Mechanism / fix

`formatRelative` buckets elapsed seconds and builds abbreviated strings directly:
```ts
if (seconds < 60) return 'just now';
if (seconds < 3600) return `${Math.floor(seconds / 60)}m ago`;
if (seconds < 86400) return `${Math.floor(seconds / 3600)}h ago`;
return `${Math.floor(seconds / 86400)}d ago`;
```

Because there's only this one function and one call site, the fix is entirely local — swap the abbreviated suffixes for full words with correct pluralization, e.g.:
```ts
const minutes = Math.floor(seconds / 60);
if (seconds < 3600) return `${minutes} minute${minutes === 1 ? '' : 's'} ago`;
const hours = Math.floor(seconds / 3600);
if (seconds < 86400) return `${hours} hour${hours === 1 ? '' : 's'} ago`;
const days = Math.floor(seconds / 86400);
return `${days} day${days === 1 ? '' : 's'} ago`;
```
No other files need to change — since `UserBadge.tsx` is the only consumer, editing `formatRelative` updates the display everywhere "ago" text currently appears in the web client.
